      heading: 'What counts as a "verified" supplier — and what does not',
      headingPl: 'Co znaczy „zweryfikowany" dostawca — a co nie znaczy',
      body: `Directory listings are not verification. A profile on Europages, Kompass, or ThomasNet confirms one thing: someone filled in a form and probably paid for the listing. It does not confirm the company still trades, its certifications are current, or the contact person is reachable.

Real verification in 2026 means four things at minimum:

1. <strong>Trade registry presence</strong> — the company exists in an official registry (KRS in Poland, Handelsregister in Germany, Companies House in the UK, Registre du Commerce in France). No registry, no supplier.
2. <strong>Valid VAT number</strong> — cross-checked in <a href="https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/vies/">VIES</a> for EU suppliers. "VAT pending" means you do not send them a deposit.
3. <strong>Working website and working email</strong> — the website loads in the last 30 days, and at least one email domain MX record resolves. Dead websites with a contact form are red flags for dormant companies.
4. <strong>Certification match</strong> — if your brief says "ISO 9001 required," the certificate number must be valid and listed on the certifying body's public registry (IAF CertSearch covers most accredited bodies).

Anything weaker than this and you are just sending RFQs into the void.`,
