      heading: 'The hidden cost math',
      headingPl: 'Ukryta matematyka kosztów',
      body: `The fully-loaded cost of a procurement professional in Western Europe runs €55-€80 per hour (salary, benefits, overhead, tools). Mid-market average sits around <strong>€60/hour</strong>. Plug that into 30 hours and one sourcing campaign costs your company <strong>€1,800 in internal time</strong> — before a single RFQ is sent.

Now annualize. A typical mid-market purchasing manager runs 20-25 campaigns per year. Even at 20 campaigns × €1,800, that is <strong>€36,000 per buyer per year</strong> spent on research. In a team of three buyers, you are approaching €110k of fully-loaded salary pointed at Google searches and follow-up chasing.

The real question is what that money does not buy. A 21-day sourcing cycle means the buyer can realistically run 17-20 campaigns per year. A 7-day cycle means 40-50. That is not a minor efficiency gain — it is <strong>2x more categories sourced competitively</strong> per headcount. And every incremental campaign you run competitively (instead of renewing the incumbent) tends to shave 8-15% off category cost. The chain:

<strong>Faster sourcing → more competitive rounds per year → more spend placed under negotiated pricing → higher margin.</strong>

If your team sources €50M of addressable spend per year and you can move an extra 30% through competitive rounds instead of renewals, at an 8% savings rate, you are leaving <strong>€1.2M on the table</strong> — not because your buyers are bad, but because they do not have the hours.`,
