      headingPl: 'Typowe błędy nearshoringu — i jak ich unikać',
      body: `Five failure patterns we see across nearshoring programs:

<strong>Starting with the wrong category.</strong> First nearshore program should be a mid-complexity category where you already have detailed specs and some flexibility on lead time. Picking your most strategic or most cost-sensitive category first guarantees friction.

<strong>Underestimating sample and audit time.</strong> European factories typically take 10-20 days to produce and ship a first sample. Asian factories are faster in this respect. Build this delta into timelines from the start.

<strong>Single-source locking.</strong> Moving 100% of volume to one nearshore supplier on the first pilot is the same single-source risk you were trying to reduce. Qualify 2-3 suppliers even if you only order from one initially.

<strong>Ignoring labor cost trajectory.</strong> Polish wages are rising 10-12% per year. Romanian wages up 14%. Turkish wages nominal growth 35-40% per year but TRY depreciation offsets some. Factor wage inflation into 3-year cost models, not just current quote.

<strong>Forgetting tooling and IP cost.</strong> If the category uses custom tooling, molds, or specifications, the move from China involves duplication (or physical transport) of tooling. Budget €10k-€80k depending on complexity. Tooling depreciation can shift the business case by 6-18 months.

The mistakes are all recoverable. They just slow programs by 2-4 months and shake internal confidence at a point where momentum matters most.`,
