      heading: 'RFQ vs RFP — a quick disambiguation',
      headingPl: 'RFQ vs RFP — szybkie rozróżnienie',
      body: `For B2B procurement, the distinction is practical:

<strong>RFQ (Request for Quotation)</strong> = you know what you want. Specifications are defined. You are asking suppliers to price it. Output: a set of comparable prices.

<strong>RFP (Request for Proposal)</strong> = you know the outcome you need. Specifications are open. You are asking suppliers to propose how to deliver it. Output: a set of solutions, each with a price.

90% of day-to-day procurement is RFQs. RFPs are for strategic categories or bespoke work (software implementations, consulting engagements, custom tooling). Automation benefits apply to both, but the workflow is different — RFPs need qualitative scoring on top of price normalization.

Rest of this post focuses on RFQ automation. RFP automation is a separate topic we cover in the offer-comparison pillar.`,
